{"title_page": "Port Wallace, Nova Scotia", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                   = Port Wallace\n| type                   = Locality \n| image_skyline          = View from rear of Halifax IKEA (45813425782).jpg\n| image_caption          = Port Wallace viewed from the opposite side of Lake Charles\n| pushpin_map            = Canada Nova Scotia\n| pushpin_label_position = none\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location within Nova Scotia\n| coordinates            = {{coord|44|41|53|N|63|32|50|W|region:CA-NS|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type         = Country\n| subdivision_name         = {{CAN}}\n| subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1        = {{NS}}\n| subdivision_type2      = [[Municipal government in Canada|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2      = [[Halifax Regional Municipality]]\n| subdivision_type3      = Community\n| subdivision_name3      = [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]]\n| subdivision_type4      = Community council\n| subdivision_name4      = [[Halifax Regional Community Council|Harbour East - Marine Drive Community Council]]\n| subdivision_type5      = District\n| subdivision_name5      = 6 - Harbourview - Burnside - Dartmouth East\n| established_title      = <!-- Founded -->\n| established_date       =\n| population_total       =\n| population_as_of       = census\n| area_total_km2         =\n| postal_code_type       = Postal code\n| postal_code            = B2W\n| area_code_type         = [[Area code]]\n| area_code              = [[Area code 902|902]]\n| blank_name_sec1        = [[Geographical Names Board of Canada|GNBC]] code\n| blank_info_sec1        = CBRRA\n| website                =\n}}\n'''Port Wallace''' is an urban locality in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], [[Nova Scotia]], Canada.\n\nIt is located on the northeastern edge of the community of [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]] and lies midway between [[Lake Micmac]] and [[Lake Charles (Nova Scotia)|Lake Charles]].\n\nIts main street is [[Nova Scotia Route 318|Route 318]] and is named the Waverley Road and Braemar Drive.  [[Shubie Park]] is a local municipal park which preserves part of the historic [[Shubenacadie Canal]] between the two lakes.\n\nThe [[forward sortation area]] for the community's [[postal code]] is B2X.\n\n==History==\nPort Wallace was established in 1861 and is named after the Honourable [[Michael Wallace (politician)|Michael Wallace]], a colonial administrator and former President of the Shubenacadie Canal Company.  The canal's eventual completion in 1861 resulted in the present-day community being named after Wallace, who died in 1831 at the time of the canal company's bankruptcy. His legacy continues today with an elementary school in the community being named after him.\n\nAfter Wallace's death, the name of the community was erroneously changed from Port Wallace to Port Wallis, after Admiral [[Provo Wallis]].  The new name was officially approved on 3 December 1953, only to be returned to the present '''Port Wallace''' on 18 February 1963.\n\nPort Wallace was home to a Mi'kmaq village, located on the banks of Lake Micmac, close to the eventual location of the canal. Some of the most significant canal work took place around Port Wallace, and many of the canal workers resided in the camp here.<ref>Donna Barnett, River of Dreams: the saga of the Shubenacadie Canal. Nimbus Publishing, 2002. P. 22-24, p. 36-37.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Neighbourhoods of Dartmouth, Nova Scotia}}\n\n[[Category:Communities in Halifax, Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:1861 establishments in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth, Nova Scotia]]\n\n\n{{HalifaxNS-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced stub|auto=yes|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                   = Port Wallace\n| type                   = Locality \n| image_skyline          = View from rear of Halifax IKEA (45813425782).jpg\n| image_caption          = Port Wallace viewed from the opposite side of Lake Charles\n| pushpin_map            = Canada Nova Scotia\n| pushpin_label_position = none\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location within Nova Scotia\n| coordinates            = {{coord|44|41|53|N|63|32|50|W|region:CA-NS|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type         = Country\n| subdivision_name         = {{CAN}}\n| subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1        = {{NS}}\n| subdivision_type2      = [[Municipal government in Canada|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2      = [[Halifax Regional Municipality]]\n| subdivision_type3      = Community\n| subdivision_name3      = [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]]\n| subdivision_type4      = Community council\n| subdivision_name4      = [[Halifax Regional Community Council|Harbour East - Marine Drive Community Council]]\n| subdivision_type5      = District\n| subdivision_name5      = 6 - Harbourview - Burnside - Dartmouth East\n| established_title      = <!-- Founded -->\n| established_date       =\n| population_total       =\n| population_as_of       = census\n| area_total_km2         =\n| postal_code_type       = Postal code\n| postal_code            = B2W\n| area_code_type         = [[Area code]]\n| area_code              = [[Area code 902|902]]\n| blank_name_sec1        = [[Geographical Names Board of Canada|GNBC]] code\n| blank_info_sec1        = CBRRA\n| website                =\n}}\n'''Port Wallace''' is an urban locality in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], [[Nova Scotia]], Canada.\n\nIt is located on the northeastern edge of the community of [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]] and lies midway between [[Lake Micmac]] and [[Lake Charles (Nova Scotia)|Lake Charles]].\n\nIts main street is [[Nova Scotia Route 318|Route 318]] and is named the Waverley Road and Braemar Drive.  [[Shubie Park]] is a local municipal park which preserves part of the historic [[Shubenacadie Canal]] between the two lakes.  \n\nThe [[forward sortation area]] for the community's [[postal code]] is B2X.\n\n==History==\nPort Wallace was established in 1861 and is named after the Honourable [[Michael Wallace (politician)|Michael Wallace]], a colonial administrator and former President of the Shubenacadie Canal Company.  The canal's eventual completion in 1861 resulted in the present-day community being named after Wallace, who died in 1831 at the time of the canal company's bankruptcy. His legacy continues today with an elementary school in the community being named after him.\n\nAfter Wallace's death, the name of the community was erroneously changed from Port Wallace to Port Wallis, after Admiral [[Provo Wallis]].  The new name was officially approved on 3 December 1953, only to be returned to the present '''Port Wallace''' on 18 February 1963.\n\nPort Wallace was home to a Mi'kmaq village, located on the banks of Lake Micmac, close to the eventual location of the canal. Some of the most significant canal work took place around Port Wallace, and many of the canal workers resided in the camp here.<ref>Donna Barnett, River of Dreams: the saga of the Shubenacadie Canal. Nimbus Publishing, 2002. P. 22-24, p. 36-37.</ref>\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n\n{{Neighbourhoods of Dartmouth, Nova Scotia}}\n[[Category:Communities in Halifax, Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:1861 establishments in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth, Nova Scotia]]\n\n{{HalifaxNS-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "stub sorting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Port_Wallace,_Nova_Scotia"}
