{"title_page": "ServiceNow", "text_new": "{{short description|American technology company}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name               = ServiceNow, Inc.\n| logo               = ServiceNow Logo 2018.png\n| image              = ServiceNowGlobalHQ.jpg\n| image_caption      = ServiceNow global headquarters in Santa Clara, CA\n| former_name        = Glidesoft\n| type               = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as          = {{ubl|{{NYSE|NOW}}|[[S&P 500]] component}}\n| industry           = [[Enterprise software]]\n| foundation         = {{start date and age|2003}}\n| founders           = {{unbulleted list|[[Fred Luddy]]|David Loo|Don Goodliffe|Bow Ruggeri}}\n| hq_location        = [[Santa Clara, California]]\n| area_served        = 5400+ customers worldwide\n| key_people         = {{unbulleted list|[[Bill McDermott]] {{small|(CEO)}}|Chirantan \"CJ\" Desai {{small|([[Chief product officer|CPO]])}}|Lara Caimi {{small|(CSO)}}|}}\n| products           = \n| services           = {{unbulleted list|[[Cloud computing]]|[[IT service management]]|Enterprise Service Management}}\n| revenue            = {{nowrap|{{Increase}} {{USD|2,608,816,000}} (2018)<ref name=\"FY2018_annual_report\">{{cite web |url=https://www.servicenow.com/content/dam/servicenow-assets/public/en-us/doc-type/other-document/earnings/Q4-Fiscal-Year-2018-Earnings-Release.pdf|title=ServiceNow Reports Record Fourth Quarter and Fiscal Year 2018 Financial Results}}{{self-published source|date=June 2019}}</ref>}}\n| operating_income   = {{nowrap|{{Increase}} {{USD|\u221242,426,000}} (2018)<ref name=\"FY2018_annual_report\"/>}}\n| net_income         = {{nowrap|{{Increase}} {{USD|\u221226,704,000}} (2018)<ref name=\"FY2018_annual_report\"/>}}\n| assets             = {{nowrap|{{Increase}} {{USD|3,879,140,000}} (2018)<ref name=\"FY2018_annual_report\"/>}}\n| equity             = {{nowrap|{{Increase}} {{USD|1,866,567}} (2018)<ref name=\"FY2018_annual_report\"/>}}\n| num_employees      = 8,666\n| num_employees_year = 2019\n| subsid             = \n| website            = {{URL|servicenow.com}}\n}}\n\n'''ServiceNow, Inc.''' (Service-now in 2011) is an American [[cloud computing]] company with its headquarters in [[Santa Clara, California]]. It was founded in 2004 by [[Fred Luddy]]. ServiceNow is listed on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] and is a constituent of the [[Russell 1000 Index]] and [[S&P 500 Index]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/servicenow-rallies-ahead-of-joining-the-s-p-500-11574273745|title=ServiceNow Rallies Ahead of Joining the S&P 500}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nServiceNow was founded as Glidesoft, Inc. in 2003 by Fred Luddy (the previous [[Chief Technology Officer|CTO]] of software companies [[Peregrine Systems]] and [[Remedy Corporation]]), and later incorporated in California in 2004.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.xconomy.com/san-diego/2017/10/03/servicenow-buys-san-diego-specialist-in-customer-experience-design/|title=Xconomy: ServiceNow Buys San Diego Specialist in Customer Experience, Design|last=Bigelow|first=Bruce V.|date=October 3, 2017|work=Xconomy|access-date=2018-05-11|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite press release|title=Glidesoft seeks San Diego area businesses to participate in Customer Advisory Program for innovative IT Service Management solution|date=January 25, 2005|publisher=GlideSoft|url=http://cdn2.hubspot.net/hubfs/2082202/Blog_Images/GlideSoft_-_PR_-_Jan_25_2005.png|access-date=2018-05-11|via=BusinessWire|format=PNG}}</ref> Luddy had previously served as [[chief technology officer]] for [[Peregrine Systems]], an enterprise software company based in San Diego, until 2002.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.xconomy.com/san-diego/2011/01/11/service-now-ceo-fred-luddy-sees-a-clear-path-to-1-billion-in-annual-revenue/?single_page=true|title=Xconomy: Service-Now CEO Fred Luddy Sees a Clear Path to $1 Billion in Annual Revenue|last=Bigelow|first=Bruce V.|date=January 11, 2011|work=Xconomy|access-date=2018-05-11|language=en-US}}<!--this citation contains a photograph of Luddy--></ref> In founding the company, Luddy intended to provide the same services previously available from the then defunct Peregrine Systems.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nUntil mid-2005, Luddy was the only employee and concentrated on developing the software which the company would offer.<ref name=\":2\" />\nThen came the first hires, five people, and raising {{US$|2.5 million}} in [[Venture capital financing|venture financing]] from [[JMI Equity]].<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2006, the company changed its name to ServiceNow.<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Abbott|first1=Martin L.|last2=Fisher|first2=Michael T.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0TjpDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT59&lpg=PT59#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Scalability Rules: Principles for Scaling Web Sites|date=2016-08-25|publisher=Addison-Wesley Professional|edition=2|page=59|isbn=978-0-13-443167-3|language=en}}</ref> In 2007, ServiceNow reported an annual revenue of {{US$|13 million}} and opened their first [[Silicon Valley]] office, in [[San Jose, California|San Jose]].<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.xconomy.com/san-diego/2011/08/09/san-diegos-servicenow-driving-hard-as-revenue-soars-expands-to-silicon-valley/?single_page=true|title=San Diego\u2019s ServiceNow Driving Hard as Revenue Soars; Expands to Silicon Valley|last=Bigelow|first=Bruce V.|date=August 9, 2011|website=|publisher=Xconomy|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref> 2007 was also the first year that the company \"went cash flow positive\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n{{As of|2011|January}}, the company had 275 employees in its San Diego, Chicago, New York, Atlanta, London and Frankfurt offices, as well as a partnership with [[Accenture]] who had more than 100 ServiceNow consultants.<ref name=\":2\" /> At this time, the company was known as \"Service-now\".<ref name=\":2\" /> By April 2011, the company had named Frank Slootman as [[chief executive officer]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn June 2012, ServiceNow became a [[Public company|publicly traded company]] following a {{US$|210 million}} [[Initial public offering|IPO]]. Shortly thereafter, the company relocated its headquarters from [[San Diego]] to [[Santa Clara, California]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> It was taken public by [[Morgan Stanley]] one month after they took [[Facebook]] public.<ref name=\"Spears\">{{cite web|first=Lee |last=Spears |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2012-06-29/servicenow-advances-in-debut-after-210-million-ipo |title=ServiceNow Advances in Debut After $210 Million IPO|publisher=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=June 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, ServiceNow acquired Mirror42, an Amsterdam-based software developer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://xconomy.com/san-diego/2013/07/09/servicenow-acquires-dutch-provider-of-performance-analytics-software/|title=ServiceNow Acquires Dutch Provider of Performance Analytics Software|last=Bigelow|first=Bruce|website=Xconomy|language=en|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, ServiceNow acquired Neebula Systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20140709005681/en/ServiceNow-Acquires-Neebula|title=ServiceNow Acquires Nebula|website=BusinessWire|language=en|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, ServiceNow acquired Intr\u00e9is.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itbrief.co.nz/story/servicenow-acquires-intreis-launches-new-grc-offering|title=ServiceNow Acquires Intrei, Launches New GRC Offering|website=ITBrief|language=en|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, ServiceNow acquired the cloud management software startup ITapp.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/press-release/servicenow-acquires-cloud-management-provider-itapp-2016-04-05|title=ServiceNow Acquires Cloud Management Provide ITapp|website=MarketWatch|language=en|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, ServiceNow acquired Brightport Security.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2016/06/01/servicenow-security-software-brightpoint/|title=ServiceNow snaps up Security Startup|last=Clancy|first=Heather|website=forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, ServiceNow acquired machine learning startup DxContinuum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/servicenow-buys-dxcontinuum-to-boost-enterprise-automation-services/|title=ServiceNow buys DxContinuum to boost enterprise automation services|last=Gagliordi|first=Natalie|website=zdnet|language=en|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, the company acquired Qlue to enhance experiences with artificial intelligence to service desk conversations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20170517005587/en/ServiceNow-Acquires-Qlue-Invests-BuildOnMe-Deliver-Intelligent|title=ServiceNow Acquires Qlue and Invests in BuildOnMe to Deliver Intelligent Automation to Everyday Enterprise Work|website=BusinessWire|language=en|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, the company acquired the San Diego [[human-centered design]] firm Telepathy, which had been founded in 2001; the acquisition doubled the size of ServiceNow's internal design agency, the Design Experience Organization.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn October 2017, ServiceNow acquired SkyGiraffe,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/servicenow-buys-mobile-platform-startup-skygiraffe/|title=ServiceNow buys mobile platform startup SkyGiraffe|last=Gagliordi|first=Natalie|website=ZDNet|language=en|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref> an enterprise mobility platform, that consequently formed the basis for ServiceNow's mobile platform offering released in March 2019. SkyGiraffe was founded by Boaz Hecht and Itay Braun in 2012, headquartered in California with R&D in Israel.<ref name=\":4\" />\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.servicenow.com/2019/servicenow-madrid-mobile.html|title=Welcome to the Now Platform Madrid Release \u2013 ServiceNow Blog|website=www.servicenow.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref>\nIn April 2018 ServiceNow acquired VendorHawk, a Software-as-Service-Management Company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/servicenow-beats-estimates-acquires-vendorhawk/|title=ServiceNow beats estimates, acquires VendorHawk|last=Gagliordi|first=Natalie|website=zdnet|language=en|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, ServiceNow acquired Parlo, an artificial intelligence / natural language understanding workforce solution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.servicenow.com/company/media/press-room/servicenow-acquires-parlo.html |title=ServiceNow Acquires Parlo, AI Workforce Solution\n|language=en|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, ServiceNow acquired FriendlyData, a company specializing in a form of [[natural language processing]] that enables queries to be asked in plain language.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20181010005931/en/ServiceNow-Simplifies-Work-Acquisition-FriendlyData|title=ServiceNow Further Simplifies Work With Acquisition of FriendlyData|website=BusinessWire|language=en|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, ServiceNow acquired Appsee Ltd., an analytics startup, that helped developers understand how users interact with their mobile apps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siliconangle.com/2019/05/13/servicenow-picks-mobile-app-analytics-startup-appsee/|title=ServiceNow picks up mobile app analytics startup Appsee|last=Deutcher|first=Maria|website=SiliconAngle|language=en|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, the company announced that CEO [[John Donahoe]] would be succeeded by [[Bill McDermott]], formerly CEO of [[SAP SE]] at the end of the calendar year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnomics.com/2019/10/23/servicenow-shakeup-no-one-saw-this-coming/|title=ServiceNow Shakeup: No One Saw This Coming|date=2019-10-23|website=Channelnomics|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, ServiceNow acquired Fairchild Resiliency Systems, a 13 person company specializing in business continuity and disaster recovery. Previous to the acquisition, Fairchild Resiliency Systems was owner of the MaestroRS app in the ServiceNow app store.\n\nIn February 2020, ServiceNow announced its acquisition of Loom Systems and Passage AI.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clearedgepartners.com/post/servicenow-unveils-earnings-and-strategy|title=ServiceNow Unveils 2019 Q4 Earnings and Strategy for 2020|last=Beyh|first=Daniel|date=2020-02-03|website=ClearEdge Partners|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n==Business model==\nServiceNow is a [[Software as a service|software-as-a-service]] provider, providing technical management support, such as [[IT service management]], to the IT operations of large corporations, including providing [[help desk]] functionality. The company's core business revolves around management of \"incident, problem, and change\" IT operational events. Their fee model was based on a cost per user (seat) per month, with that cost ranging down from {{US$|100}}.<ref name=\":2\" /><!-- this citation covers the entire paragraph -->\n\n==See also==\n* [[IT service management]]\n* [[DevOps]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n{{Major Internet companies}}\n\n[[Category:Software companies based in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Santa Clara, California]]\n[[Category:Cloud computing providers]]\n[[Category:Cloud applications]]\n[[Category:Service-oriented (business computing)]]\n[[Category:Information technology management]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Software companies established in 2003]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:2012 initial public offerings]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2003]]\n[[Category:Software companies of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American technology company}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name 